<p>Anger, indignation and rage are three words that dominate the mind space every time one hears of a woman being violated. Add a fourth - disgust - at the extent of perversion in India's male dominated society. What is missing is Respect. Perhaps in no other society  is the power of femininity expressed so powerfully as in India. The idea of Shakti, or divine feminine power suffuses Indian culture. Sadly, the reality for a female in modern India is quite different. She lives in a world where she is the object of assault and exploitation because she is physically weak. India, and we need to acknowledge it,  has become a dangerous jungle where men have taken the form of predators who think nothing of attacking any woman - from a baby to a grandmother-- to satisfy their lust.  </p>

<p>Stree has taken many forms and is deeply ingrained in our psyches through its different avatars and manifestations - Durga, Lakshmi, Saraswati - and yet we allow bestiality to overpower us and desecrate the female form. Whatever be our spiritual traditions, our actual history of the treatment of women has been quite dismal.  In the 19th century, it took a westernised Indian, Raja Rammohan Roy and the British administrators to press for the end to the terrible custom of sati. However, there were other and earlier voices like  Shahjanand Swami, the founder of the Swaminarayan sect who preached against sati and the third Sikh Guru Amardas and other Sikh leaders, who, too, condemned it. But there was largely silence from the orthodox. </p>

<p>The role played by women in the Indian national movement was exemplary and to a great degree this was an outcome of the attitudes of its principal leaders, especially Mahatma Gandhi and Jawaharlal Nehru. It was Prime Minister Nehru who pushed through the Hindu Code Bills of 1955 and 1966 giving equality to men and women in marriage, succession and adoption. He did this over the opposition of  hardliners in his own party who opposed such moves in the name of tradition. </p>

<p>Influential Hindutvaorganisations talk a great deal about cultural nationalism. But they have done little by way of leading movements against the social evils of our times, which include  femalefoeticide and child marriage. Not to say that the Congress of today is any better. It is difficult to forget the Rajiv Gandhi government's attitude to the Shah Bano judgment. </p>
<p>The effort to ensure equality to those who hold up half our sky requires effective laws and their implementation. It also needs harsh and swift punishment for the predators who prey on women because of their sex. There is only one way of doing this—through a zero-tolerance approach to sexual crimes and misdemeanours.  </p>

<p>But there is only that much legislation and laws can achieve, as is clear by the prevalence of child marriage, dowry killings, and the abandonment of widows in Varanasi and Mathura. What is required is a social and cultural movement for change. This is the track that Prime Minister Narendra Modi has taken in his Independence Day address when he called on each of us to act against female foeticide and sexual assault on women and linked his call for a clean India with the provision of toilets across the country, especially for women.</p>

<p> Mr Modi understands well that it is the transformation of the so-called small things that will ring in the new India. You may aspire to be an IT or manufacturing hub, but to actually become one, you need to be quite a different society, one that treats its women as human beings and encourages and, indeed, cherishes their contribution to society. </p>
  
<p>This is the aim of the "I am Shakti" movement which seeks to light the moral flame within all of us and make us aware of the need to respect and honour women. We all know of women as mothers, sisters, spouses and daughters. But we also need to know them simply as other human beings who deserve to be treated as such.</p>

